\begin{abstract}
Standard educational tests don't tell us much about what a student can really do, because every learner gets the same questions regardless of ability. We describe a working prototype---a Multi-Agent MCQ-based Student Competency Analysis System---that grades responses and studies learner competency across several cognitive domains through a fully LLM-driven pipeline. Our starting point was the multi-agent competency-building framework of Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024}: we adapt their Assess--Predict--Oversee--Transit (APOT) model to a question-based assessment setting. Where Outay \textit{et al.} rely on deterministic KPI metrics inside an AR vocational training loop, we reinterpret the four APOT agents (LSAA, SOLMA, SOLPA, SOLTA) as LLM-powered reasoning modules that work over natural language signals instead of numeric thresholds. The implementation is Django 4.2 plus a CrewAI pipeline of three specialized agents running on Google Gemini 2.5 Flash---an MCQ Evaluator, a Difficulty Predictor, and an Adaptive MCQ Overseer. To keep the UI snappy, we split the work into two layers: a synchronous rule-based fallback for immediate responses, and a background multi-agent pipeline for the heavier AI-driven competency analysis. Questions are generated on the fly by the LLM, so there's no pre-calibrated Item Response Theory model or static item bank in the loop. A design-level walkthrough shows the system behaves consistently across three cognitive domains: Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability.
\end{abstract}

