% -------------------------------------------------------
\section{Introduction}
% -------------------------------------------------------

Most educational tests today still follow a one-size-fits-all recipe, handing every student the same questions regardless of their current ability. In practice, strong students get bored by items that feel trivial and weaker students get overwhelmed, so either way the test misses what the learner at the edges can actually do \cite{weiss2004}. Feedback tends to be generic too, which hurts personalization and slows down learning \cite{vygotsky1978,mislevy2003}.

Computerized Adaptive Testing (CAT) is the usual answer to this, adjusting difficulty as a student responds \cite{lord1980}. The catch is that most CAT systems lean on Item Response Theory (IRT), which wants large, pre-calibrated item banks with validated statistical parameters \cite{hambleton1985}. That's a hard sell for smaller institutions, and the selection machinery can feel like a black box to educators. We looked at IRT early on and ruled it out for two very practical reasons: we had no calibrated item bank of our own (and building one would mean running pilot studies before the system could even be used), and the probabilistic machinery is difficult to explain to teachers who are supposed to trust the system's decisions.

Recent LLM work opens up a different angle---let the adaptation logic live inside intelligent agents. An LLM agent can reason about correctness and response time together and make context-aware difficulty decisions using natural language rules. Those rules sit in the agent's backstory as plain English, which is far easier for a non-ML educator to read (and argue with) than a set of IRT parameters.

Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024} introduced the APOT (Assess--Predict--Oversee--Transit) model, managed by a Multi-Agent System (MAS) for competency building. Their design uses four agents: LSAA, SOLMA, SOLPA, and SOLTA. Their framework was built for AR-based vocational training though, and it depends on deterministic KPI metrics pulled from sensor streams. Our setting looks quite different: a student sits in front of a browser and picks one of four options. There are no KPIs to read off hardware---only correctness and response time. So we borrowed the cyclic stages and role separation and dropped them into a fully LLM-driven, question-based environment.

The contributions of this work are:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item A three-agent CrewAI pipeline on Gemini 2.5 Flash that maps to the APOT agents (SOLMA, SOLPA, SOLTA), replacing formula-driven scoring with LLM-native contextual reasoning.
    \item A dual-layer difficulty adaptation scheme---synchronous rule-based fallback paired with asynchronous multi-agent LLM analysis---and LLM-driven dynamic question generation that removes the static item bank requirement.
    \item An interpretable, prompt-engineered adaptation mechanism that skips IRT pre-calibration while staying responsive and explainable.
    \item A working implementation with concrete tooling choices (Django, CrewAI, Gemini 2.5 Flash, MySQL) that other practitioners can reuse or critique.
\end{enumerate}

% -------------------------------------------------------
\section{Related Work}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{Multi-Agent Systems in Education}
Multi-Agent Systems (MAS) have been a popular thread in educational technology for a while \cite{wooldridge2009}. The APOT model \cite{outay2024} uses four agents: \textbf{LSAA} for modality preferences, \textbf{SOLMA} to track current performance, \textbf{SOLPA} to predict learner potential, and \textbf{SOLTA} to decide when a learner should move between competency stages. Together they compute a Learning Index and a Competency Index. It's a clean design, but it was shaped around vocational AR training, and the assumptions don't all transfer to digital question-based assessment. In our case, there are no physical KPIs to read---just correctness and time---so each agent reasons in natural language over those two signals, and the LSAA role ends up folded into domain-aware question generation rather than living as a separate modality-profiling agent.

\subsection{Computerized Adaptive Testing}
CAT has been studied since the 1970s and is generally considered a solid way to personalize assessment \cite{weiss2004}. Most CAT systems rest on IRT, where each question carries difficulty, discrimination, and guessing parameters \cite{lord1980}. The approach is statistically rigorous, but the item banks it needs take serious time and money to calibrate \cite{hambleton1985}, and the probabilistic machinery tends to be opaque to educators. Where Lord \cite{lord1980} and Hambleton and Swaminathan \cite{hambleton1985} build selection rules on estimated item parameters, we drop the parameter estimation step entirely and let an LLM agent reason over observable signals using transparent natural language heuristics. The trade-off is non-determinism, which we discuss honestly in Section~\ref{sec:limitations}.

\subsection{LLM-Augmented Assessment Frameworks}
LLMs have made their way into educational systems for feedback, tutoring, and content generation \cite{chen2023}. Frameworks like CrewAI and AutoGen \cite{liang2023} both support multi-agent LLM workflows. We went with CrewAI for a specific reason: its declarative role/goal/backstory model mapped almost directly onto the APOT agent definitions we were reproducing, and \texttt{Process.sequential} chained three tasks with barely any boilerplate. AutoGen is more flexible for open-ended multi-turn agent conversations, but our pipeline is a straight three-step chain where each agent runs once per question, so we didn't need that flexibility. Bloom's taxonomy \cite{bloom1956} informs our Easy/Medium/Hard scheme. Reinforcement learning \cite{sutton2018} and Bayesian student models \cite{conati2002} are alternatives we considered, but both want training data we don't have---Conati \textit{et al.}'s Bayesian networks in particular need logged tutoring interactions that work well for long-running tutors but not for our short single-session format. Unlike systems that limit the LLM to feedback generation, we hand the entire competency analysis pipeline over to LLM agents.

