\subsection{Assessment Workflow and APOT Mapping}
Each session runs a per-question adaptive loop over 20 questions. For every question we record the selected option and the time it took. The Evaluator decides whether the answer was right, the Predictor classifies the question's difficulty, and the Overseer looks at both outputs and picks the difficulty for the next question. Three cognitive domains are supported---Reasoning, Aptitude (aliases: Quantitative Aptitude, Quant), and Verbal Ability (aliases: Verbal, English)---with topic normalization keeping the vocabulary consistent.

The original APOT model \cite{outay2024} runs a cyclic Assess, Predict, Oversee, Transit loop. Our mapping: \textit{Assess} becomes the Evaluator Agent (SOLMA role) tracking correctness; \textit{Predict} becomes the Predictor Agent (SOLPA role) classifying difficulty; and both \textit{Oversee} and \textit{Transit} map onto the Overseer Agent (SOLTA role), which synthesizes the earlier analyses and decides on the transition. We don't have a dedicated LSAA-style agent---that function ends up inside domain-aware question generation, since a question-only setting simply doesn't give enough signal to infer learning style the way an AR setup can.

\subsection{Dual-Layer Difficulty Adaptation}
Decoupling UI responsiveness from the heavier pipeline was a design decision we made early. The \textbf{Synchronous Layer} fires the moment an answer is submitted and applies a deterministic mapping: if correct, Easy$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Hard, Hard$\rightarrow$Hard; if incorrect, Hard$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Easy, Easy$\rightarrow$Easy. The next question is generated at that difficulty and sent back in the JSON response, so the UI updates in under a second. The \textbf{Asynchronous Layer} kicks off a daemon thread that runs the full Evaluator $\rightarrow$ Predictor $\rightarrow$ Overseer pipeline, persists its analysis to \texttt{QuestionPerformance} and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory}, and updates \texttt{final\_difficulty}. The thread closes its DB connection in a \texttt{finally} block so connections don't leak.

Why split it? During development we initially tried running the CrewAI pipeline synchronously on the request thread, and the first few questions had 4--7 second waits between submission and the next question loading. That felt broken enough that we moved the pipeline off the request path.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\section{Multi-Agent Framework}
% -------------------------------------------------------

All three agents run on Gemini 2.5 Flash through CrewAI's LLM interface at temperature 0.7, executing sequentially with context passed between tasks. We ended up going with Gemini 2.5 Flash because its latency was low enough that the async pipeline usually finishes before the student submits the next question, the free-tier quota made iterative development cheap, and on short classification-style prompts we couldn't see a quality gap against the Pro variant during informal checks.

\subsection{MCQ Evaluator Agent}
This agent fills the SOLMA (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent) role, corresponding to the APOT \textit{Assess} phase---watching the quality of each immediate response, much like the original SOLMA watches current performance \cite{outay2024}. Its job is narrow: act as a fair and accurate MCQ examiner. Given the question, correct answer, student's answer, and time taken, it decides whether the answer is right and writes a one-line justification. We set \texttt{allow\_delegation=False} so factual judgment doesn't bleed into difficulty reasoning. The output is a binary correctness verdict plus a short explanation---the factual foundation everything downstream relies on.

\subsection{Difficulty Predictor Agent}
Mapped to the SOLPA role and the APOT \textit{Predict} phase, this agent labels the current question as Easy, Medium, or Hard based on the Evaluator's verdict and the response time. Its backstory spells the heuristic out: ``Fast + Correct = Easy. Slow + Correct = Medium. Wrong = Hard.'' That reflects the well-known idea that response time plus correctness is a reasonable behavioral proxy for difficulty \cite{weiss2004}. Crucially, we don't hard-code any time thresholds---the LLM decides what ``fast'' or ``slow'' means in context. In practice we noticed the agent tends to treat anything under roughly 15 seconds as fast and anything over 40 as slow, but that's emergent rather than something we set.

\subsection{Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent}
The Overseer plays the SOLTA role and covers both the \textit{Oversee} and \textit{Transit} phases. Where the original SOLTA decides when a learner moves between competency stages \cite{outay2024}, our Overseer decides when and how to move between difficulty levels---which is a direct reflection of how the student's competency is developing. It reads the Evaluator and Predictor outputs as context and produces two things: a confirmed current difficulty, and a recommended next difficulty. Its backstory encodes adaptive rules inspired by the Zone of Proximal Development \cite{vygotsky1978} and Bloom's taxonomy \cite{bloom1956}. On a \textbf{correct} answer: Easy$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Hard, Hard$\rightarrow$Hard (or Medium). On an \textbf{incorrect} answer: Hard$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Easy, Easy$\rightarrow$Easy (to rebuild confidence). We leave \texttt{allow\_delegation=True} on this one so it can check back with the earlier agents if something is ambiguous. The output follows a structured format with four labelled lines (``Questions Difficulty'', ``Next Question Difficulty'', ``Reasoning'', ``Recommendation''), which we parse line-by-line via keyword matching, falling back to ``Medium'' if parsing fails.

\subsection{CrewAI Orchestration}
The three agents are wired into a single \texttt{Crew} with \texttt{Process.sequential}, \texttt{memory=False}, and \texttt{max\_rpm=10} to stay inside Gemini's free-tier rate limit. Task~3 (the Overseer) declares \texttt{context=[task1, task2]} so it sees both earlier outputs. One \texttt{crew.kickoff()} call runs the whole thing and returns the Overseer's output as a string. Fig.~\ref{fig:pipeline} shows the complete pipeline.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\section{Implementation}
\label{sec:implementation}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{Environment and Agent Wiring}
Development was done on Ubuntu 22.04 LTS (Intel Core i5, 16~GB RAM) and cross-checked on Windows 11 for portability. The stack is Python 3.11, Django 4.2.11, MySQL 8.0.36 (via \texttt{mysqlclient}), CrewAI 0.28.x, and \texttt{google-generativeai} pinned at 0.7.x for stability. Supporting packages: \texttt{python-dotenv}, \texttt{redis-py} for the optional Celery queue (not used in the default synchronous deployment), and \texttt{gunicorn} behind Nginx. We tested a deployment on a small DigitalOcean droplet (2 vCPU, 4~GB RAM), which was more than enough for single-user load. All three agents are instantiated via CrewAI's \texttt{Agent} class with Gemini at temperature 0.7. Each agent's \texttt{role}, \texttt{goal}, and \texttt{backstory} fields carry the natural-language spec described in Section~IV.

\subsection{Question Generation}
Questions are generated on demand through a direct \texttt{google-generativeai} call rather than a CrewAI agent, since generation isn't strictly part of the APOT reasoning loop. The prompt asks for exactly one MCQ at a given topic and difficulty, with options A--D, one correct answer, and a list of already-asked questions for the session to avoid. It enforces a strict JSON schema (\texttt{question}, \texttt{options}, \texttt{correct\_answer}, \texttt{difficulty}, \texttt{topic}) so parsing stays predictable. The output text is stripped of accidental code fences (Gemini sometimes adds \texttt{```json} markers despite instructions not to) before \texttt{json.loads}.

\subsection{Runtime Flow and Robustness}
When the student hits ``Submit'', the browser POSTs the selected option, question index, and time to \texttt{/submit\_answer/}. The Django view validates the session, appends the answer, and runs the synchronous rule-based fallback to compute the next difficulty---so the UI doesn't wait on the LLM. A daemon \texttt{threading.Thread} is then spawned to run the CrewAI pipeline in the background while the view calls the question generator for the next question and returns JSON. The background thread typically finishes in 2--4 seconds, writes the \texttt{QuestionPerformance} and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory} rows, updates \texttt{final\_difficulty}, and closes its thread-local DB connection in a \texttt{finally} block. Because each question has its own \texttt{question\_number} key, overlapping threads write to different rows and we don't see race conditions.

Several fallbacks are layered in. If the API key fails, the pipeline returns a canned ``Medium''/``Medium'' result with a reasoning note, so the session is never interrupted. Question generation retries transient errors (HTTP 503, 429, 500, and messages containing ``UNAVAILABLE'', ``overloaded'', or ``high demand'') up to three times with a $(\text{attempt}+1)\times 2$ second backoff. If every retry fails and JSON parsing still doesn't succeed, a stub fallback question is returned. Sessions are tied to a UUID linking the transient state in \texttt{request.session} to a durable \texttt{StudentTestResult} row, and status follows a small state machine: \texttt{in\_progress} $\rightarrow$ \texttt{completed} / \texttt{auto\_submitted} / \texttt{expired}. The 20-minute timer is enforced twice---JavaScript countdown in the frontend, plus a backend check that recomputes elapsed time from the stored \texttt{start\_time} on every request. Students can also skip and revisit: skipped indices are stored and revisited after the linear pass ends, which interleaves forward progress with deferred items.

