\subsection{Behavioral Trace}
Table~\ref{tab:trace} shows expected outputs for a few representative scenarios. The system steps up difficulty when students answer quickly and correctly, which is consistent with mastery of the easier material. A correct-but-slow response lands at Medium, reflecting effortful but successful performance. Incorrect answers---fast or slow---get classified as Hard and trigger a step down, which is exactly what the adaptive rules call for. All of this lines up with Vygotsky's Zone of Proximal Development \cite{vygotsky1978}: keep the student right at the edge of their current ability without tipping them into either frustration or boredom.

