\subsection{Competency Analytics and Data Models}
Beyond per-question adaptation, the dashboard does longitudinal tracking. Competency Index (CI) is computed as a weighted average over the ten most recent completed tests using harmonic weights (weight = 1/rank), so recent performance has more pull than older averages. Per-domain accuracy across Aptitude, Reasoning, and Verbal is tracked separately, and the weakest domain is flagged for targeted feedback. The leaderboard sorts students into bands---Expert ($\geq$85), Advanced ($\geq$70), Intermediate ($\geq$50), Beginner ($<$50). Three models persist everything: \texttt{StudentTestResult} (session metadata, initial and final difficulty, score, status, timestamps, JSON fields for answers and adaptive analysis); \texttt{QuestionPerformance} (per-question detail with a uniqueness constraint on (test, question\_number), and the full reasoning text from CrewAI); and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory} (a focused record of the Overseer's per-question output).

\subsection{Why LLM-Native Adaptation Helps Here}
Handing all difficulty reasoning to LLM agents instead of deterministic formulas paid off in a few ways we didn't fully anticipate. Adaptation rules can be rewritten in natural language without touching any scoring code, which makes the system easier to maintain than we expected. The agents also pick up on contextual nuance that rigid formulas can't express---the Predictor reads ``fast'' and ``slow'' in context rather than relying on fixed second-thresholds. The full chain of reasoning is right there in the agent output too, so educators get a natural language explanation for every difficulty decision, which directly supports the explainability goals of the APOT framework \cite{outay2024}. Skipping pre-calibrated IRT parameters lets us deploy in any domain without first building an item bank \cite{hambleton1985}, and LLM-driven question generation removes what is traditionally the biggest bottleneck---new domains just need a topic name and a difficulty level.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\section{Limitations}
\label{sec:limitations}
% -------------------------------------------------------

There's plenty we want to be honest about. Even with Flash, the CrewAI pipeline sits at roughly 2--4 seconds end-to-end per question in our environment, and occasionally spikes to 6 seconds or more when the API is under load---that's basically the reason the dual-layer fallback exists, and it also means the AI-driven analysis is always slightly behind the student's actual progress. At temperature 0.7, the same input can produce slightly different outputs; we picked 0.7 because lower temperatures (0.2--0.3) sometimes caused the Overseer to skip the ``Reasoning:'' line entirely. The trade-off is real and we haven't fully tuned it---the line-by-line parser with ``Medium'' defaults is a safety net, not a substitute for determinism. Cost-wise, Gemini 2.5 Flash has a free tier that covers development and light usage, but at scale (hundreds of concurrent students generating 20+ pipeline invocations each) the numbers stop being trivial, and batching or caching (neither of which we do yet) would be necessary. Because questions come from an LLM with a simple prompt, the generator can favor certain phrasings or cultural references (English-centric examples, Western names) that don't generalize to every student population, and we don't yet have a mechanism to detect or correct for this---a production deployment would need at least a light human review loop. The whole pipeline also rests on the agent backstories, and in our own testing small rewording changes in the Overseer's backstory have produced noticeably different transition behavior, which makes the system powerful but fragile. The CrewAI pipeline runs with \texttt{memory=False}, so longer-horizon patterns---a student who is consistently fast on Medium but stalls on Hard across \textit{several} questions---aren't visible to the agent during a session. And finally, this paper presents a design and implementation analysis only: we haven't yet run a controlled study comparing the adaptive system against a static MCQ baseline with real students, so claims about engagement and competency tracking are framed at the design level. That study is the immediate next step.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\section{Conclusion and Future Work}
\label{sec:conclusion}
% -------------------------------------------------------

What we built is an Adaptive Multi-Agent Student Competency Analysis System that brings the APOT framework \cite{outay2024} into a fully LLM-driven adaptive testing setting. Mapping the Evaluator, Predictor, and Overseer (as SOLMA, SOLPA, SOLTA) onto three CrewAI agents running on Gemini 2.5 Flash let us replace deterministic scoring and IRT pre-calibration with prompt-engineered LLM reasoning over correctness and response time. The LSAA function shows up indirectly through domain-aware question generation across Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability. The dual-layer architecture---synchronous rule-based fallback plus asynchronous multi-agent AI pipeline---shows that production-grade adaptive competency analysis can coexist with computationally heavy LLM pipelines, and LLM-driven question generation cuts out the traditional need for pre-curated, statistically validated item banks. Next steps include user studies with diverse student populations (checking how well LLM-predicted difficulty labels match expert annotations), extending the LSAA function with an explicit learning-style profiling agent, enabling session-level memory (\texttt{memory=True}) so the Overseer can plan over longer horizons, prompt-optimization work to reduce output variability, comparing LLM-based adaptation decisions against IRT-based ground truth on standardized item banks, and scaling out to concurrent multi-user assessment sessions with instructor-facing dashboards using the Celery and Redis infrastructure that's already in the stack.

